(425, 793, 'In a Congolese sawmill, trunks are waiting to be shipped to the markets of the Middle Kingdom. © Lu Guang / Greenpeace<br />\n<br />\nLess than a year after the blockage of nearly 500 trucks carrying Congolese redwood in Zambia, new cases of illegal logging are reported around Kundelungu Park in southern DRC. Local civil society fears consequences for the environment.<br />\n<br />\nLusaka did not move. Any transit of Congolese redwood on Zambian territory remains prohibited. This does not seem to cool down some loggers in the former border Katanga. In any case, according to several sources within the local civil society, new cases of mukula cuts have been recorded in recent weeks in this southern part of the DRC.<br />\n<br />\nFor now, \"it is not a question of a general resumption of the exploitation of the wood\", notes Mgr. Fulgence Muteba, bishop of the diocese of Kilwa-Kasenga, in Haut-Katanga, famous notably for his commitment in favor of the protection of nature. \"It is the negative impact of the persistence of these tree felling on the environment that worries us,\" said another member of the civil society who requested anonymity.<br />\n<br />\nExploitation of red wood, impact on the environment<br />\n\"If we are not careful, soon, the former Katanga will be in the situation of some areas of southern Africa,\" he warns. Local civil society is particularly concerned about the indirect long-term consequences of deforestation, such as those that led to food shortages in Mozambique, the food crisis in Malawi last year, and the worst drought in the world. the second largest city in South Africa.<br />\n<br />\n\"It\'s unacceptable that at the same time wild deforestation resumes in Lualaba\", in the south of the DRC, denounces the civil society activist who points the responsibility of \"children of\" - hear the descent of the authorities of this new province - to be behind the recent illegal redwood felling.<br />\n<br />\nIn March, Moïse Katumbi, former governor of today\'s dismembered Katanga, was already denouncing the threat to the region\'s wildlife. \"More than 100 hectares of forest [were] cut every day on the Kasenga and Pweto roads,\" warned the presidential candidate.<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n<br />\nA truck carrying red wood breaks down on the Kasenga-Pweto road in southeastern DRC. © DR<br />\n<br />\nThree weeks later, Lusaka intercepted some 499 trucks carrying Congolese redwood. Kinshasa sent a mission there. A month later, the exploitation of redwood in the DRC was banned.<br />\n<br />\nWhen Amy Ambatobe, Minister of the Environment and Sustainable Development, arrived in May, she said she had tried to \"put in place a framework\" for restarting redwood operations. in the former Katanga. \"But an instruction from the presidency of the Republic has formally asked us to postpone everything,\" he says.<br />\n<br />\nRedwood still banned from exit?<br />\n\"At the moment, we can not exploit redwood,\" says the minister. According to him, \"all state structures, including customs, have been educated on this subject. They can not authorize the removal of redwood from Congolese territory \".<br />\n<br />\n\"Under these conditions, how could farmers continue to cut wood, when they know they can not export it? He asks.<br />\n<br />\nOn the ground, Catholic clergy close to the case report that a certain Kabongo Ngoy - who claims his proximity to the presidential family - \"is busy collecting logs cut before ban in the Boa region and trucked to Kalemie , in order to reach Tanzania bypassing Zambia. \"<br />\n<br />\nWhile another operator, \"the Mukalay named him took over the exploitation in Mbayo\", near the Upemba National Park, according to the same sources. Minister Amy Ambatobe promises to \"deploy [his] services\" to verify the veracity of all these allegations from local civil society.<br />\n<br />\n<br />\nwe want to see the black investors take a look at this', NULL, 0, '', 0, '2018-03-17